I have another equation f of x,

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:18.000
y, z. This is the same equation,
the Schršdinger equation, only it

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:22.000
has different boundary conditions.
It has k2 as the boundary

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:26.000
conditions. And when I solve it for
k2 boundary conditions,

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:30.000
I get s2. Here is the power of
linearity.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:55.070
The power of linearity is if I come
across f of x,

00:25:55.070 --> 00:26:00.150
y, z equals k1 plus k2,
if it is a linear equation,

00:26:00.150 --> 00:26:05.220
I don't have to go and solve it all
over again. Instead I can write

00:26:05.220 --> 00:26:10.300
with impunity the solution will be
s1 plus s2. And that saves a lot of

00:26:10.300 --> 00:26:15.380
time. Linearity is the desirable
way to go if you can manage.

00:26:15.380 --> 00:26:20.460
What does this mean? Linearity of
